               <interp inst="t18400406-1280" type="date" value="18400406"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18400406-1280-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1280-18400406 t18400406-1280-offence-1 t18400406-1280-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1280. <persName id="def1-1280-18400406" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1280-18400406" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1280-18400406" type="age" value="22"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1280-18400406" type="surname" value="HARRISON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1280-18400406" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN HARRISON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18400406-1280-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18400406-1280-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18400406-1280-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp> for a misdemeanor.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1418" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1418" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1418" type="surname" value="PEARSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1418" type="given" value="JONATHAN"></interp>JONATHAN PEARSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an ironmonger, in partnership with Thomas and John Pearson. I deal with Mr. Griffiths—on the 26th of March the prisoner came and said he wanted one of the best bottle-jacks—I got him one to look at—he asked the price, and said it was for Mr. Griffiths, of No. 2, Burton-crescent—he said he would have that one, and asked to see a lamp which was in the window—he said it was just the sort of article Mr. Griffiths had been speaking about—I wished to send it home, but he said he would take them, and said, "That is an excellent guard you had put up in Mr. Griffiths's winery"—I let him have the articles, believing he came from Mr. Griffiths—I had some recollection of having seen him before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What pas the value of the bottle-jack? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> 14<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and the lamp 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1419" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1419" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1419" type="surname" value="PEARSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1419" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS PEARSON</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 26th of March, after the prisoner had been with my brother, he came and said he wanted the lamp he had just looked at—I said, "Which do you mean?"—he pointed to one on the counter, and said it was for Mr. Griffiths—I said, "You had better let us send it"—he said, "No, you had better let me take it," and I gave it to him—between half-past four and five o'clock he came again for a dozen table knives and forks, he said Mr. Griffiths had a party that day, and they were all in a bustle—I asked what sort be would have—he said what Mr. Griffiths had were balance ones—he selected a dozen at 36<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and took them away with him—in two hours suspicions were raised, and I went to see Mr. Griffiths—I parted with the goods, believing he came from Mr. Griffiths—he also said to me, "That was an excellent guard you put up a twelve-month ago."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1420" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1420" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1420" type="surname" value="GRIFFITHS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1420" type="given" value="GEORGE STOKEHOUSE"></interp>GEORGE STOKEHOUSE GRIFFITHS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a solicitor. I deal with Pearson and Co.—I did not authorise the prisoner to go for these articles—I knew nothing about it—I never received the goods—he did not live</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184004060202"></xptr>
               <p>with me—I have known him some years—he is a connexion of mine by marriage, and knew I dealt with Mr. Pearson—he bore a very excellent character till lately.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1421" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1421" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1421" type="surname" value="RIDEWOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1421" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM RIDEWOOD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a broker and curiosity-dealer, in Cleveland-street. I bought this bottle-jack, and lamp, on the 26th, of the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What did you give for them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for the two—I had seen the prisoner two or three times before—he had sold me trifling things on each occasion—I think the time before that he sold me an old box, and some old newspapers—I gave him 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for the box—he sold me an old shot-belt and powder-flask for 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. together—I do not recollect what I bought of him besides—I do not keep an account of what I buy—he was dressed as he is now—he brought me the bottle-jack about two o'clock, and the lamp at the same time—I know these knives were offered to me, between five and six o'clock—I said I did not want them, and offered 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1422" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1422" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1422" type="surname" value="DOWLING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1422" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DOWLING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clothes-salesman, in Cleveland-street. I bought the knives of the prisoner, for 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. they were quite new.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had you seen him before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, several times—I bought some trowsers of him, and other things.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18400406-1280-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
